{
  "text": "Although we did not identify the anatomical localization of the ␣7 nAChRs involved, it is likely that both central and peripheral components contribute to the effects seen. Areas of the hypothalamus, particularly the lateral hypothalamus that regulates appetite, contain both ␣7 and ␣4␤2 nAChRs [CITATION_1] . Evidence suggests that activation of presynaptic ␣7 nAChRs on GABAergic terminals in the lateral hypothalamus decreases appetite by inhibiting the activity of melanin-concentrating hormone neurons [CITATION_2] . It is possible that the decreases we observed in food consumption and weight gain involve activation of CNS ␣7 nAChRs because TC-7020 is readily accessible to the brain (oral bioavailability in rats, 33%; brain/plasma ratio ϭ 0.4 at 4 h postdose) and the effects of TC-7020 were blocked by the ␣7 antagonist MLA, which has also been shown to cross the blood-brain barrier [CITATION_3] . It is interesting to note that the effects of TC-7020 were also blocked by the JAK2 inhibitor AG-490 because the metabolic feedback on adiposity, which is mediated by leptin receptors in the hypothalamus, also involves receptor-JAK2 interactions [CITATION_4] . This raises the intriguing possibility that in the db Ϫ obese mice, which lack an active leptin receptor, the ␣7 nAChR may substitute for the leptin receptor in the activation of JAK2. This would re-establish the feedback loop normally activated by adipose-derived leptin that signals a decreased need for food intake. Consistent with this is the observation that nicotine directly increases leptin signaling in rat hypothalamus [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
